ide basic health insurance to everybody. a single-payer health care plan, a universal health care plan. and that's what i'd like to see. and as all of you know, we may not get there immediately. because first we have to take back the white house, we have to take back the senate, we have to take back the house." ((candidate full), remarks at afl-cio forum, chicago, il, 6/30/03) <b> </b></p><p>in 2008, (candidate full) said he would only support a single-payer system if "starting from scratch." (candidate last): "[i] never said that we should try to go ahead and get single payer. what i said was that if i were starting from scratch, if we didn't have a system in which employers had typically provided health care, i would probably go with a single-payer system." ((candidate full), cnn/congressional black caucus (PARTY NAME) presidential candidates debate, myrtle beach, sc, 1/21/08) <b><i> </i></b></p><p align="center">key (PARTY NAME) doubt that (candidate full)'s plan will pass <u> </u></p><p>senate (PARTY NAME) are already raising doubts about the likelihood that the (candidate last) plan will pass:  </p><p>senior congressional (PARTY NAME) are "maneuvering to lower public expectations" of (candidate full)'s health care promises. "congressional (PARTY NAME) are backing away from healthcare reform promises made by their two presidential candidates, saying that even if their party controls the white house and congress, sweeping change will be difficult. it is still seven months before election day, but already senior (PARTY NAME) are maneuvering to lower public expectations on the key policy issue." (manu raju, "dems hedge on healthcare," <i>the hill</i>, 4/23/08) <b> </b></p><p>(candidate full)'s promises to deliver universal care on the campaign trail "may not match the political reality on capitol hill." "for some senators, the promises made by sens. (candidate full) (d-ill.) and hillary rodham (candidate last) (d-n.y.) outside of washington may not match the politi